comment:
Hi Andy, 
Just caught your commentary regarding the above subject. Sadly you made some erroneous and libelous statements regarding Judge Nichols. In fact he is a very senior British judge. The equivalent rank in the US would be a very senior Federal Judge. So he is not a man to be dismissed lightly. Especially as unlike in the US, in the UK senior Judges are not political appointees, in fact NO active British Judge can be politically appointed. In the UK the Judiciary are truly independent. Therefore, you can only attain high judicial office on strictly merit alone. 
The point I am about to make is that the case you were commenting on was not really between Ms Heard and Mr Depp, but between Mr Depp and  "The Sun" newspaper, for its comments regarding the physical exchanges between the couple, and the use of the phrase "Wife beater". Whilst much colour was given to the court regarding the couples relationship. The legal point was: Was the Sun entitled to use the phrase? The Judge decided that as there was evidence that violence had taken place between the couple, and that there was evidence that Mr Depp had assaulted his wife whether in self defence, provocation or otherwise Mr Depp had struck his wife, therefore the Sun was entitled to use that phrase in this case. 
In regards everything else that you picked out, this was merely part of the preamble before handing down his decision, much of which was dismissive of all the back and forth that the interested parties wanted to put on record. The Judge stuck to the letter of the law; whether the paper was entitled to use that phrase in this context, sadly in the literal determination of the law, the answer was yes.

comment:
Nobody has any business criticizing what one does with the money they have/are awarded etc. Nobody can make one promise to donate money to charity. One does not have to do this.  One can take a divorce settlement and use the funds to live a lavish lifestyle if one wants to. Would some people criticize it? Sure! But, let's face it, if one lives in a public eye, there is always going to be somebody criticizing. At the end of the day, there is nothing inherently wrong to sped one's divorce settlement the way they want to.
Having said this, saying publicly, that the whole sum is going to be donated to charity and then not following up is a disgusting and manipulative way to sway the public opinion and make oneself look good. Only an awful, awful human being does that!  
Repulsive, revolting and repugnant!

comment:
@Popcorned Planet - Interesting video, Andy. Didn't get any commercials when you signaled them, just letting you know that first.

This looks like White & Co., Depp's accountants (not lawyers) informed the the CHLA Foundation of the $3.5 million pledge with their first installment and had they continued to make installments, they would have kept on referring to that pledge and given an ongoing account of the tally towards the $3.5 million.  Since they were told to give the money directly to Amber, they did not continue making installments.  

Any money that Amber did give towards the CHLA might not have referenced that specific pledge and so the CHLA might have been just asking Amber if any more money should be expected from White & Co. on her behalf or if it was only coming from her now.

I'm not saying that it doesn't look sketchy, but it does need further investigation if you actually follow ONLY the information in the documents and not leap to ANY conclusions (no matter how small or large).  As for the cars, getting caught on camera and all of that, not sure what to make of it but the information is certainly interesting.
